normally like to show it.

00:17:50.790 --> 00:17:56.420
I'd rather have it so it's zoomed in
a bit so that we could look around.

00:17:56.420 --> 00:17:58.250
But it's a way for people to see it.

00:17:58.420 --> 00:18:02.550
Their clientele, you know,
is Fortune 500 companies.

00:18:02.700 --> 00:18:04.450
Broadband is not the issue.

00:18:04.630 --> 00:18:08.720
In fact, some of these people have
like T3 lines to their homes.

00:18:08.790 --> 00:18:12.050
So, you know,
as big of files as we wanted to make,

00:18:12.050 --> 00:18:13.800
they were fine with that.

00:18:14.240 --> 00:18:17.410
Interiors, the animations that
we were talking about.

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:22.020
So like the seat, I can rotate, you know,
show different accessories.

00:18:22.240 --> 00:18:23.310
This seat doesn't do much.

00:18:23.380 --> 00:18:24.240
It's a lame seat.

00:18:24.460 --> 00:18:28.240
We have, you know,
but we have other seats.

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:30.790
We have other seats where they
actually unfold and there's like

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:32.260
a little place for your drinks.

00:18:32.260 --> 00:18:34.200
We had to animate the drinks coming in.

00:18:34.200 --> 00:18:35.200
You know, all that good stuff.

00:18:35.200 --> 00:18:39.180
So tables, table on there.

00:18:39.200 --> 00:18:43.200
So again, showing that, you know,
you can -- okay, come on.

00:18:43.200 --> 00:18:44.200
We can get there.

00:18:44.200 --> 00:18:44.810
There we go.

00:18:44.880 --> 00:18:47.190
We can -- we show that, you know,
you have these fold-out tables,

00:18:47.190 --> 00:18:48.700
that type of thing.

00:18:48.700 --> 00:18:53.290
So their big thing was to animate
showing the clients or prospective

00:18:53.770 --> 00:18:58.200
clients all the possibilities that if
they rented this jet for only $359,000,

00:18:58.200 --> 00:19:02.940
$359,000 per year,
that they could open up a folding table.

00:19:03.540 --> 00:19:05.020
So --

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:10.100
But actually, they have found that this
technology has improved sales.

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:11.400
They did a little demo CD.

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:18.360
They sent out demo CDs with PDFs to,
I think, about 1,000 prospective clients.

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:21.010
And out of those 1,000
prospective clients,

00:19:21.010 --> 00:19:22.570
they had a response of 30.

00:19:22.570 --> 00:19:25.020
Now, you may say, well, 30 people.

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:27.290
Yeah, but 30 people at 300,000.

00:19:27.310 --> 00:19:30.450
I'll take 30 people at
300,000 every day of the week.

00:19:30.500 --> 00:19:34.050
So if we can go back to my demo machine,
please.

00:19:38.100 --> 00:19:42.980
So that was a really good project
for us and it started us thinking.

00:19:42.980 --> 00:19:44.800
This is the National Air and
Space Museum,

00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:45.950
part of the Smithsonian.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:47.970
It's my current project right now.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:51.610
It's rather a huge project.

00:19:52.110 --> 00:19:57.000
We're shooting over 200 aircraft
and 144 space artifacts.

00:19:57.120 --> 00:19:59.920
The original project was
going to go for eight months.

00:20:00.170 --> 00:20:02.000
We're now up to two years.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:05.000
There are a guesstimate that we'll be
working on the project for two years.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:08.430
I got an email saying, "Oh my God,
you won't believe it.

00:20:08.430 --> 00:20:13.000
We may have more work." I'm like,
"Two years?"

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:16.240
You know, there's only so much I can
love airplanes after two years.

00:20:16.490 --> 00:20:21.910
But anyway,
so we're shooting a lot of stuff.

00:20:21.970 --> 00:20:25.930
We're creating a lot of QuickTime VR,
and we're doing a lot of really cool,

00:20:26.340 --> 00:20:27.210
cutting-edge stuff.

00:20:27.340 --> 00:20:32.260
So let's talk about some of the
things leading up to the project.

00:20:32.260 --> 00:20:35.920
So my initial contact with the museum,
people want to know, like,

00:20:35.920 --> 00:20:37.290
how do you get this work?

00:20:38.050 --> 00:20:40.900
So I was doing work for another museum,
and somebody told me that

00:20:40.900 --> 00:20:43.700
the Smithsonian was thinking
of doing something similar,

00:20:43.700 --> 00:20:47.260
and this museum was so proud that
they were ahead of the Smithsonian.

00:20:47.260 --> 00:20:49.590
So as soon as I heard that,
I picked up the phone and

00:20:49.590 --> 00:20:52.640
started calling the Smithsonian,
saying, "I hear you want some

00:20:52.670 --> 00:20:55.890
VR shot." And they were like,
"VR what?" You know, so I had to, like,

00:20:55.970 --> 00:20:57.440
find the right people.

00:20:57.440 --> 00:21:02.100
This project took me two years
just to get it moving forward.

00:21:02.120 --> 00:21:05.840
I've been working on it for two years,
talking to curators,

00:21:05.860 --> 00:21:11.410
talking to different departments,
at the Smithsonian, going through a whole

00:21:11.800 --> 00:21:13.680
bunch of issues with them.

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:17.910
My biggest thing is my
contract is 35 pages long,

00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:20.570
and 20 pages relate to insurance.

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:24.560
You know, like, there's no way I could
insure the right flyer.

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:27.740
You know, I just don't,
I can't get a policy big enough.

00:21:27.810 --> 00:21:31.630
So there's these new things I keep
having to learn as we go through.

00:21:31.690 --> 00:21:32.620
Prototyping.

00:21:32.620 --> 00:21:36.280
Prototyping became really big
when I started working with the

00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:41.380
Smithsonian and other larger museums,
because for a visual thing, you know,

00:21:41.380 --> 00:21:42.660
they're not visual.

00:21:42.830 --> 00:21:45.570
You know, I tell them, "Well, here,
we can do this,

00:21:45.680 --> 00:21:48.420
we can do that," and I show that to them,
and they, like, don't get it.

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:50.700
So I have to use their actual pieces.

00:21:51.160 --> 00:21:55.170
There's a joke in Chicago that, you know,
if you shoot an apple pie,

00:21:55.170 --> 00:21:56.670
a peach pie won't do.

00:21:56.790 --> 00:21:59.710
You have to shoot an apple pie, you know,
to show to an art director.

00:21:59.780 --> 00:22:03.540
So, anyway, so same thing with this.

00:22:03.540 --> 00:22:07.420
I had to actually go in and
start shooting aircraft.

00:22:07.420 --> 00:22:09.820
I had to go in and start shooting
aircraft and build prototypes

00:22:09.820 --> 00:22:14.360
with their stuff before they could
visualize what they wanted to do.

00:22:14.360 --> 00:22:16.020
Expectations.

00:22:16.020 --> 00:22:18.360
They had very low expectations.

00:22:18.360 --> 00:22:19.560
We were actually in
there showing them stuff,

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:21.860
and they were like,
"I never knew I could do this.

00:22:21.860 --> 00:22:26.730
This is so cool." You know,
does it cost much?

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:29.240
That's a byword, funding.

00:22:29.240 --> 00:22:32.220
Funding is always a big
byword at the Smithsonian.

00:22:32.220 --> 00:22:33.460
Clients' concerns.

00:22:33.470 --> 00:22:36.680
We had a lot of concerns in the
very beginning when we started

00:22:36.770 --> 00:22:40.770
shooting because there was
like touching the artifacts.

00:22:40.950 --> 00:22:45.140
They have very specific rules
about touching a 50-year-old

00:22:45.140 --> 00:22:47.560
airplane or an 80-year-old aircraft.

00:22:47.920 --> 00:22:49.440
Mac versus PC.

00:22:49.440 --> 00:22:56.580
I was really concerned about this because
the Smithsonian has an IT department

00:22:56.580 --> 00:22:59.810
that's the IT department from hell?

00:22:59.880 --> 00:23:02.220
You know, they're like, "Apple?

00:23:02.610 --> 00:23:05.740
No, we can't do that." You know,
I'm like, "No, no, it's easy.

00:23:05.740 --> 00:23:06.690
It's QuickTime.

00:23:06.890 --> 00:23:08.350
You know, take the Apple part out.

00:23:08.450 --> 00:23:10.950
Just think QuickTime." "But
that's an Apple product.

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:14.440
It won't run on our servers." No,
it's not an issue, believe me.

00:23:14.600 --> 00:23:19.110
So I spend -- it took two weeks for
them to hook up an airport extreme.

00:23:19.120 --> 00:23:23.560
They had two people at the facility
to hook up the extreme because they

00:23:23.660 --> 00:23:27.570
weren't sure how well it would go,
and they dedicated all day.

00:23:28.850 --> 00:23:32.380
So, it took 30 seconds to
plug in the Ethernet.

00:23:32.380 --> 00:23:33.190
It's a government job.

00:23:33.200 --> 00:23:36.950
Remember,
two people plug in that Ethernet cable.

00:23:37.160 --> 00:23:40.360
And then I'm on the Mac and I say, "Okay,
I have Signal." And they're like, "No,

00:23:40.360 --> 00:23:41.140
you can't.

00:23:41.230 --> 00:23:45.350
It can't be that easy." "No, no,
it's a Mac thing."

00:23:45.620 --> 00:23:49.780
So, it took me two weeks to get that 30
seconds for them to plug that in.

00:23:49.780 --> 00:23:55.280
So, dealing a lot with convincing
them that the Mac is the way

00:23:55.280 --> 00:23:58.560
to go as far as easeability,
but on QuickTime, no issues.

00:23:58.600 --> 00:24:04.000
Showed them running QuickTime on Windows,
showed them QuickTime streaming server,

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.450
showed them all the stuff that
they could do without changing

00:24:07.450 --> 00:24:10.790
the way they're working,
and they were very impressed.

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:12.770
They were impressed
that it doesn't break,

00:24:12.780 --> 00:24:14.770
they were impressed
that it actually works,

00:24:14.780 --> 00:24:17.190
they were impressed that they
wouldn't have to hire extra

00:24:17.330 --> 00:24:18.690
people to make it happen.

00:24:18.700 --> 00:24:20.830
So, it was a good thing for us.

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:26.100
Hardware,
Apple Computer and Rhonda Strahton,

00:24:26.100 --> 00:24:30.220
they've been very good to us and
they've loaned us some computers to use.

00:24:30.220 --> 00:24:34.430
So we're using Nikon and
Canon digital cameras.

00:24:34.520 --> 00:24:36.740
Remember,
I'm that digital guy in the other world.

00:24:36.740 --> 00:24:43.010
So we shoot with the Nikon
D1Xs and on the Canon side,

00:24:43.010 --> 00:24:45.140
the Canon D1S.

00:24:45.320 --> 00:24:49.720
Make really high meg files,
we'll talk about that later.

00:24:50.220 --> 00:24:54.450
Bogan Lighting, Kydan VR heads, Dr.

00:24:54.550 --> 00:24:58.820
Lewis has made us that
specialized motorized head,

00:24:58.860 --> 00:25:03.800
Lexar Media with the CF memory cards,
and GreyTag Macbeth for color.

00:25:03.800 --> 00:25:06.310
I've now served my country
and God because I've got

00:25:06.370 --> 00:25:07.790
all my sponsors out there.

00:25:07.800 --> 00:25:09.270
Thank you.

00:25:10.200 --> 00:25:11.400
So lots of hardware.

00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:13.000
Oh, let's go back for one quick thing.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:16.240
We, oops, I'm going the wrong way here.

00:25:16.250 --> 00:25:17.940
I hate when that happens.

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:20.030
We have these rolling carts.

00:25:20.130 --> 00:25:22.680
So there's an aircraft in the background.

00:25:22.680 --> 00:25:26.470
We have the Canon 1DS,
and we fire the cameras right

00:25:26.610 --> 00:25:29.700
through firewire into the computers.

00:25:29.700 --> 00:25:34.390
We've had a host of special applications,
not a host, a few special applications

00:25:34.390 --> 00:25:37.510
written for us,
but basically we've found it's

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:40.840
very expedient to shoot right to
the hard drives of the computers,

00:25:40.860 --> 00:25:43.820
saves us time downloading,
and we can also visually

00:25:43.840 --> 00:25:45.540
see the images right away.

00:25:45.600 --> 00:25:49.310
We're using five computers, two laptops.

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:51.730
There's two photographers.

00:25:51.910 --> 00:25:53.210
We have volunteers.

00:25:53.290 --> 00:25:55.060
We actually have more volunteers now.

00:25:55.060 --> 00:25:58.300
The Smithsonian has
dedicated staff to us,

00:25:58.300 --> 00:26:02.000
and we have one dedicated
janitorial staff.

00:26:02.090 --> 00:26:03.680
That's what CES is.

00:26:03.680 --> 00:26:04.650
It's our janitor.

00:26:04.660 --> 00:26:05.920
We have our own project.

00:26:05.920 --> 00:26:09.000
We have a private janitor
because photographers are messy.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:11.790
So...

00:26:12.150 --> 00:26:14.200
This is the interior of the new museum.

00:26:14.200 --> 00:26:15.380
It's called the Hasi Center.

00:26:15.380 --> 00:26:19.050
It's 200 feet wide and 1,000 feet long.

00:26:19.150 --> 00:26:21.330
And museums,
the reason why we got involved,

00:26:21.400 --> 00:26:24.050
or one of the reasons we got
involved with them is there's

00:26:24.050 --> 00:26:25.800
a love-hate thing at museums.

00:26:25.800 --> 00:26:29.360
We want you to come and see
all of our great artifacts.

00:26:29.360 --> 00:26:31.750
And you get there,
and don't get too close.

00:26:31.750 --> 00:26:32.480
Back up.

00:26:32.580 --> 00:26:33.990
Don't touch that.

00:26:34.020 --> 00:26:37.900
So it's this thing of,
they want you to come and see everything,

00:26:37.900 --> 00:26:40.840
but they don't want
you to touch anything.

00:26:41.240 --> 00:26:44.870
And then the other issue is that a lot
of the airplanes are now hanging so that

00:26:44.970 --> 00:26:47.110
you couldn't even get up close to them.

00:26:47.140 --> 00:26:50.620
So one of the reasons that
QuickTime VR is a major asset to

00:26:50.710 --> 00:26:55.670
them is that there'll be 100 kiosks
spread out throughout the museum.

00:26:55.680 --> 00:26:58.890
And as you go through the museum,
you'll start to see

00:26:59.330 --> 00:27:00.770
groupings of aircraft.

00:27:00.860 --> 00:27:04.180
That aircraft will be on the kiosk,
and now you can start seeing up

00:27:04.340 --> 00:27:06.340
close what you're seeing from afar.

00:27:06.380 --> 00:27:10.300
And I'll show you some
samples in just a minute.

00:27:10.670 --> 00:27:13.710
Color management was a
very big deal for us.

00:27:13.840 --> 00:27:17.200
Besides the fact that Smithsonian has
exacting standards on,

00:27:17.200 --> 00:27:20.820
like, if something is printed,
it has to be reproduced faithfully,

00:27:20.820 --> 00:27:23.800
just managing all these
different cameras.

00:27:23.800 --> 00:27:27.000
We found out that the different cameras
shoot color a little differently.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:30.990
So Apple has this really cool
technology called ColorSync,

00:27:31.130 --> 00:27:33.480
and now QuickTime is
supported by ColorSync,

00:27:33.480 --> 00:27:35.500
so my life is so much easier.

00:27:35.500 --> 00:27:39.240
And Apple was nice enough to fly out.

00:27:39.240 --> 00:27:43.200
Kevin O'Connor, he's a color specialist
that teaches for Apple,

00:27:43.200 --> 00:27:48.280
and Gray Tag Macbeth loaned the
calibrator so we could calibrate

00:27:48.280 --> 00:27:51.870
all our LCDs and come up with the
look-up tables for the cameras

00:27:51.870 --> 00:27:53.520
so that everything matches.

00:27:53.520 --> 00:28:00.140
I can shoot any camera that we have,
even going across brands, you know,

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:05.380
whether it's Nikon or Canon,
and I can match within 5% the color

00:28:05.660 --> 00:28:08.700
using ColorSync and ColorSync.

00:28:09.290 --> 00:28:11.660
So we have a couple of tools
out there from Gray Tag Macbeth.

00:28:11.870 --> 00:28:16.370
So it became a very good thing because
nothing's worse than going through a VR,

00:28:16.380 --> 00:28:18.990
especially a multiple-row VR,
and seeing that the

00:28:19.110 --> 00:28:20.750
color shifts for one row,
right?

00:28:20.780 --> 00:28:23.150
Just, you notice it right away,
it's not a good thing,

00:28:23.160 --> 00:28:24.320
don't want to go there.

00:28:24.340 --> 00:28:25.000
Okay.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:26.390
So color.

00:28:26.780 --> 00:28:28.950
Next thing is custom hardware.

00:28:29.190 --> 00:28:31.180
No one airplane is alike.

00:28:31.200 --> 00:28:34.530
You know, there are always, you know,
variations and stuff.

00:28:34.730 --> 00:28:37.920
And people were asking, like,
how do you rotate that, you know?

00:28:37.920 --> 00:28:39.040
You know, do you walk around it?

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:42.700
Well, if you walk around,
if you do the marking, you know,

00:28:42.700 --> 00:28:45.980
every 10 degrees around the
facility and walk around,

00:28:45.980 --> 00:28:47.750
then the plane starts to look jerky.

00:28:47.940 --> 00:28:52.000
It doesn't come out as smooth as
if you rotate the aircraft itself.

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:57.060
So, you know,
I'm always fighting budgets, you know,

00:28:57.060 --> 00:28:58.840
just like any government institution.

00:28:58.840 --> 00:29:00.030
I'm just a contractor.

00:29:00.040 --> 00:29:01.580
I'm not even the photographer anymore.

00:29:01.580 --> 00:29:02.700
I'm just a contractor.

00:29:02.700 --> 00:29:07.010
And so we're always fighting budgets,
and I've come up with all

00:29:07.020 --> 00:29:08.840
the hardware we could buy.

00:29:08.850 --> 00:29:11.040
I could buy commercially to do that,
and they were like, great,

00:29:11.080 --> 00:29:12.120
we have no money for that.

00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:13.410
Okay, well, let me think about it.

00:29:13.460 --> 00:29:18.080
So there's these things called baskets,
and the baskets are what they

00:29:18.080 --> 00:29:19.480
move the aircraft around.

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:22.160
They actually use them on
aircraft carriers to move fighters

00:29:22.240 --> 00:29:23.630
into tight corners and stuff.

00:29:23.680 --> 00:29:25.960
So we bought a bunch of these baskets.

00:29:25.960 --> 00:29:30.290
This is two-inch steel pipe,
and we have special fittings made

00:29:30.300 --> 00:29:35.910
so we can slide the airplane into
wherever we need to get so it's

00:29:35.930 --> 00:29:37.920
centered over its rotation point.

00:29:37.960 --> 00:29:38.180
Okay.

00:29:38.360 --> 00:29:44.100
So we have these, and there's about 150
to 200 pounds of weight.

00:29:44.140 --> 00:29:45.520
There's a steel plate.

00:29:45.670 --> 00:29:49.920
There's a piece of plywood and duct tape,
because no good project can

00:29:49.920 --> 00:29:51.150
survive without duct tape.

00:29:51.160 --> 00:29:54.640
And that's put on the floor,
and that's our center point,

00:29:54.640 --> 00:29:57.500
and then two people at both ends
of the airplane start pushing it.

00:29:57.500 --> 00:30:00.840
And every 10 degrees
that's marked on the floor,

00:30:00.840 --> 00:30:03.600
they know they should stop,
and then we shoot another picture.

00:30:03.600 --> 00:30:06.760
Now, on occasion,
I found out that the floor

00:30:06.760 --> 00:30:09.400
in our first location,
it wasn't level.

00:30:09.500 --> 00:30:13.130
You know, you get 10,000 pounds rolling,
and the mast wants to

00:30:13.130 --> 00:30:14.200
get to that low point.

00:30:14.220 --> 00:30:15.680
It's pretty tough to stop it.

00:30:15.860 --> 00:30:20.100
So another one of those
things that we learned.

00:30:20.570 --> 00:30:21.290
Lighting.

00:30:21.450 --> 00:30:23.440
We had a lot of issues with lighting.

00:30:23.440 --> 00:30:25.540
How do you get light into these cockpits?

00:30:25.540 --> 00:30:27.200
How can you get into tight places?

00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:31.300
Again, lots of ideas.

00:30:31.300 --> 00:30:35.100
We ended up buying $7 fluorescent bulbs.

00:30:35.300 --> 00:30:39.700
Digital cameras have great
capabilities to white balance in

00:30:39.780 --> 00:30:42.630
multiple color spectrum settings.

00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:45.480
We used these fluorescent bulbs.

00:30:45.480 --> 00:30:50.120
We went out and tested a bunch
of them and found a particular

00:30:50.120 --> 00:30:51.720
brand that was pretty consistent.

00:30:51.720 --> 00:30:53.770
We used those on stands.

00:30:53.800 --> 00:30:54.500
We hang them.

